(In this note, we reach a consensus that # of observations is \(n\) and # of features (predictor variables) is \(k\).)

Import the dataset.

library(base)
data(state)

states<-as.data.frame(state.x77[,c("Murder", "Population",  
                                   "Illiteracy", "Income", "Frost")])

library(car)
scatterplotMatrix(states,spread=FALSE, lty.smooth=2,main="Scatter Plot Matrix")

Figures on the diagonal line show the density plot of each predictors; other figures show the scatter plots between predictors.

Test normality of residuals

library(car)

fit <- lm(Murder ~ Population + Illiteracy + Income + Frost, data=states)
qqPlot(fit, labels=row.names(states), id.method="identify",
       simulate=TRUE, main="Q-Q Plot")

##       Nevada Rhode Island 
##           28           39

If the simulated line is approximately close to \(y = x\), then we can maintain the residual is normally distributed.

From the figure above, we can discover that residuals of Nevada and Rhode Island tend to be larger, then they are possibly outliers.

Next, we show another method to visualized residuals.

residplot <- function(fit, nbreaks=10) {
  z <- rstudent(fit)
  hist(z, breaks=nbreaks, freq=FALSE,
       xlab="Studentized Residual",
       main="Distribution of Errors")
  rug(jitter(z), col="brown")
  curve(dnorm(x, mean=mean(z), sd=sd(z)),
        add=TRUE, col="blue", lwd=2)
  lines(density(z)$x, density(z)$y,
        col="red", lwd=2, lty=2)
  legend("topright",
         legend = c( "Normal Curve", "Kernel Density Curve"),
         lty=1:2, col=c("blue","red"), cex=.7)
}

residplot(fit)

Test independence of residuals

durbinWatsonTest(fit)
##  lag Autocorrelation D-W Statistic p-value
##    1      -0.2006929      2.317691   0.272
##  Alternative hypothesis: rho != 0
  • lag = 1 means test \(H_0: \rho = 0\) where \(e_t = \rho e_{t-1} + v_t\).
  • Autocorrelation = -0.20 means the \(Corr(e_t,e_{t-1}) = - 0.20\).
  • D-W Statistic \(d \triangleq \frac{\sum\limits_{t = 2}^T(e_t - e_{t-1})^2}{\sum\limits_{t = 1}^Te_t^2}\), we reject \(H_0\) when \(d\) is either too small or too large.
  • p-value = \(0.298 > 0.05\) means we cannot reject \(H_0: \rho = 0\) at \(\alpha = 0.05\) significance level. Thus, we maintain that residuals are independent.

Test linearity

library(car)
crPlots(fit)

The \(X_k\) partial residual can be thought of as the response variable \(Y\) corrected for all predictor variables except \(X_k\).

The linear model is \[Y = \beta_0 + \beta_1 X_1 + \cdots + \beta_{k-1}X_{k-1} + \beta_kX_k +\varepsilon.\]

Then the \(X_k\) partial residual is defined as \[e_{X_k} \triangleq \varepsilon + \beta_kX_k = Y - \beta_0 - \beta_1 X_1 - \cdots - \beta_{k-1}X_{k-1}.\]

The component plus residual plot is so called Partial residual plot, which is the scatter plots composed of \((X_k,e_{X_k})\). Since the nonlinear relation between \(Y\) and \(X_k\) is described in the \(\varepsilon\) generated by OLS, then we can obtain the extent and direction of linearity between \(Y\) and \(X_k\) by the scatter plot of \(X_k\) partial residual \(e_{X_k}\) and \(X_k\) itself.

If the component plus residual plot shows a linear relation, then we maintain that linear assumption is met and the form of linear model seems to be appropriate for the dataset.

Test homoscedasticity

library(car)
ncvTest(fit)
## Non-constant Variance Score Test 
## Variance formula: ~ fitted.values 
## Chisquare = 1.746514, Df = 1, p = 0.18632
spreadLevelPlot(fit)

## 
## Suggested power transformation:  1.209626

From the result of ncvTest, p-value is \(0.186 > 0.05\), thus we cannot reject the null hypothesis: the variance is constant. Additionally, the recommended power transformation 1.21 is close enough to 1, which means we do not necessarily need to perform any transformation.

Moreover, from the Spread-Level Plot above, we discover that the studentized residual is close to a horzinal line, which indicates the variance is constant.

Test multicollinearity

library(car)
vif(fit)
## Population Illiteracy     Income      Frost 
##   1.245282   2.165848   1.345822   2.082547
sqrt(vif(fit))>2
## Population Illiteracy     Income      Frost 
##      FALSE      FALSE      FALSE      FALSE

\[VIF_j = \frac{1}{1-R_j^2}\] where \(R_j^2\) denotes the \(R^2\) in the linear model \(x_j \sim x_{all\ except\ j}\).

Obviously, if \(x_j\) can be interpreted by other variable, then \(R_j\) tends to be large and thus \(VIF_j\) tends to be large. Generally, we maintain that \(x_j\) has multicollinearity with other variables if \(VIF_j > 4\).

Test outliers

library(car)
outlierTest(fit)
##        rstudent unadjusted p-value Bonferroni p
## Nevada 3.542929         0.00095088     0.047544

The outlierTest reports the largest absolute studentized residual.

From the result of outlierTest, we discover that Nevada has the largest studentized residual. Since Bonferroni \(p = 0.048 < 0.05\), thus we cannot reject \(H_0\): Nevada is an outlier at \(\alpha = 0.05\) significance level.

Test high leverage points

hat.plot <- function(fit) {
  p <- length(coefficients(fit))
  n <- length(fitted(fit))
  plot(hatvalues(fit), main="Index Plot of Hat Values")
  abline(h=c(2,3)*p/n, col="red", lty=2)
  identify(1:n, hatvalues(fit), names(hatvalues(fit)))
}
hat.plot(fit)

## integer(0)

We take \(2\frac{k}{n}\) and \(3\frac{k}{n}\) as the judgement standard, the points whose \(H_{ii}\)s are greater than the judgement standard will be considered as high leverage points.

Test influential points

cutoff <- 4/(nrow(states)-length(fit$coefficients)-2)
plot(fit, which=4, cook.levels=cutoff)
abline(h=cutoff, lty=2, col="red")

If the Cooks distance is greater than \(\frac{4}{n - k - 1}\), then we maintain it is an influential point. Generally we usually use 1 as the alternative of \(\frac{4}{n-k-1}\).

Remark: The Cooks distance is defined as \[D_i \triangleq \frac{\sum\limits_{j = 1}^n(\hat{Y_j} - \hat{Y}_{j,(i)})^2}{k\sigma^2}\] where \(\hat{Y}_{j,(i)}\) denotes the \(j^{th}\) predicted value when the \(i^{th}\) observation is removed from the model.

Combination test of outliers, high leverage points and influential points.

influencePlot(fit, id.method="identify", main="Influence Plot",
              sub="Circle size is proportional to Cook's distance")

##                 StudRes        Hat       CookD
## Alaska        1.7536917 0.43247319 0.448050997
## California   -0.2761492 0.34087628 0.008052956
## Nevada        3.5429286 0.09508977 0.209915743
## Rhode Island -2.0001631 0.04562377 0.035858963

From this plot we can explicitly figure out the outliers, high leverage points and influential points.

Test added variable

avPlots(fit, ask=FALSE, onepage=TRUE, id.method="identify")

For each predictor \(X_k\) , plot the residuals from regressing the response variable \(Y\) on the other \(k-1\) predictors versus the residuals from regressing \(X_k\) on the other \(k-1\) predictors.

My understanding: The \(Y|others\) residuals represent the part of \(Y\) not explained by all the variables other than \(X_k\). The \(X_k|others\) residuals represent the part of \(X_k\) not explained by other variables. If the line is horizonal, then it follows that the other variables have already been able to fit \(Y\) perfectly. Otherwise, if the line is NOT horizonal, it indicates \(Y\) have NOT been learned completely by other variables, i.e., we should necessarily add \(X_k\) into this model.

Moveover, The slope of the line fitted to the points in the added variable plot is equal to the regression coefficient when \(Y\) is regressed on all variables including \(X_k\), i.e.,

\[\begin{equation} \begin{aligned} & Y = \beta_0 + \beta_1 X_1 + \cdots + \beta_{k-1}X_{k-1} + \beta_kX_k + \varepsilon_{Y|all}\\ & Y = \theta_0 + \theta_1 X_1 + \cdots + \theta_{k-1}X_{k-1} + \varepsilon_{Y|others}\\ & X_k = \gamma_0 + \gamma_1X_1 + \cdots + \gamma_{k-1}X_{k-1} + \varepsilon_{X_k|others}\\ \Rightarrow\ & \varepsilon_{Y|others} = 0 + \beta_k \varepsilon_{X_k|others} + \varepsilon_{Y|all} \end{aligned} \end{equation}\]

Added-variable plots are so called Partial regression plots.

Power transformation (for normality)

summary(powerTransform(states$Murder))
## bcPower Transformation to Normality 
##               Est Power Rounded Pwr Wald Lwr Bnd Wald Upr Bnd
## states$Murder    0.6055           1       0.0884       1.1227
## 
## Likelihood ratio test that transformation parameter is equal to 0
##  (log transformation)
##                            LRT df     pval
## LR test, lambda = (0) 5.665991  1 0.017297
## 
## Likelihood ratio test that no transformation is needed
##                            LRT df    pval
## LR test, lambda = (1) 2.122763  1 0.14512

From the report we can see that the estimated power is 0.61, close to 1. Thus no transformation need to be performed. Moreover, according to p-values, we should reject \(\lambda = 0\) and cannot reject \(\lambda = 1\).

Power transformation (for linearity)

boxTidwell(Murder~Population+Illiteracy,data=states)
##            MLE of lambda Score Statistic (t) Pr(>|t|)
## Population       0.86939             -0.3228   0.7483
## Illiteracy       1.35812              0.6194   0.5388
## 
## iterations =  19 
## 
## Score test for null hypothesis that all lambdas = 1:
## F = 0.23214, df = 2 and 45, Pr(>F) = 0.7938

The results suggest trying transformation \(Population^{0.87}\) and \(Illiteracy^{1.36}\) to achieve greater linearity. But the score tests for Population \((p = 0.75)\) and Illiteracy \((p = 0.54)\) suggest that neither variable needs to be transformed.
